 ('346', '2981', '11', '1', 'en_us', '3', '', '{\"typeId\":\"11\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"The EdNavigator Guide to Catholic Schools in New Orleans\",\"slug\":\"the-ednavigator-guide-to-catholic-schools-in-new-orleans\",\"postDate\":1486419360,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"50\":[\"2980\"],\"49\":\"<p>You might not realize it, but there are more than 80 Catholic schools in the greater New Orleans area. All told, they serve a total of around&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.nola.com\\/education\\/index.ssf\\/2015\\/09\\/for_catholic_schools_new_plan.html\\\">37,000 students<\\/a>. For reference, public schools in Orleans Parish enroll approximately 49,000 students. For families, Catholic schools represent a substantial portion of the school landscape \\u2013 and an important option.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Today, we\\u2019re releasing a&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/catholicschoolguide.ednavigator.com\\/\\\">new online guide<\\/a>&nbsp;to help New Orleans families who are considering Catholic schools understand the process and explore schools that might be right for their children. It features profiles of each school, frequently asked questions, information on scholarship programs, and an interactive Find a School tool. It\\u2019s the first time all of this information has been compiled in one publicly accessible online location.<\\/p>\\r\\n<h3>Why a guide to Catholic schools?<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>Over the last decade, New Orleans has invested heavily in its system of school choice and the infrastructure necessary to support it. Most notably, it adopted a universal enrollment system,&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.enrollnola.org\\/\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\" rel=\\\"noreferrer\\\">OneApp<\\/a>, to make the process of applying to public schools easier and fairer for families. Parents can use the system to view available schools and apply to those they prefer all at once. They also have access to the&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/neworleansparentsguide.org\\/\\\">New Orleans Parents Guide to Public Schools<\\/a>, Family Resource Centers, and other sources of information to help them make their choices.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>That\\u2019s not the case for the Catholic school system, however. Families interested in sending their children to Catholic schools have to research and apply to each school separately, and the process, requirements and timelines for applying differ from school to school. Then there\\u2019s the added complexity of applying for the three different kinds of scholarships available to lower-income students, which involves unraveling a whole new tangle of timelines and eligibility criteria.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>All of this translates to a lot of work and stress for parents. Overwhelmed by the prospect of researching schools, submitting applications, and figuring out the finances, many give up and don\\u2019t bother considering Catholic schools at all. It effectively puts off-limits a wide swath of local schools, particularly for parents who may not have the time or resources to deal with all the logistical demands. &nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n<h3>We wanted to make it easier.<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>Catholic schools have a long history in New Orleans, and many families love the values- and faith-based education they provide.&nbsp; We know Catholic schools aren\\u2019t right for everyone, but we believe that families should be aware of ALL of their school options and empowered to pursue any school that might be a good fit for their children. Confusing processes and unclear information should never stand in their way.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>The guide was created with great cooperation from the Office of Catholic Schools at the Archdiocese of New Orleans.&nbsp; We see it as a work in progress. Our team spent time surveying and meeting with school leaders to hear what they wanted to share with prospective families about their schools, and we are grateful to all the educators who contributed to it. Not all schools provided full information, but we plan to update the school profiles with additional data as we receive it. In the future, we also hope to add new information that gives families greater insight into each school and its success with students, in particular.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>For now, we hope the guide serves as a useful starting point for families who are interested in Catholic schools and want to narrow down their options. Check it out at&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/catholicschoolguide.ednavigator.com\\/\\\">www.catholicschoolsguide.ednavigator.com<\\/a>&nbsp;and please share it with anyone who might benefit.<\\/p>\",\"82\":\"The EdNavigator Guide to Catholic Schools in New Orleans features profiles of 80+ schools, frequently asked questions, information on scholarship programs, and an interactive Find a School tool.\",\"86\":[\"2978\"],\"85\":\"\"}}', '2017-02-08 21:11:02', '2017-02-08 21:11:02', 'ef80c778-74ae-4135-8ca3-38bab1e8ad1b'),
 ('347', '2981', '11', '1', 'en_us', '4', '', '{\"typeId\":\"11\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"The EdNavigator Guide to Catholic Schools in New Orleans\",\"slug\":\"the-ednavigator-guide-to-catholic-schools-in-new-orleans\",\"postDate\":1486419360,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"50\":[\"2980\"],\"49\":\"<p>You might not realize it, but there are more than 80 Catholic schools in the greater New Orleans area. All told, they serve a total of around&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.nola.com\\/education\\/index.ssf\\/2015\\/09\\/for_catholic_schools_new_plan.html\\\">37,000 students<\\/a>. For reference, public schools in Orleans Parish enroll approximately 49,000 students. For families, Catholic schools represent a substantial portion of the school landscape \\u2013 and an important option.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>Today, we\\u2019re releasing a&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/catholicschoolguide.ednavigator.com\\/\\\">new online guide<\\/a>&nbsp;to help New Orleans families who are considering Catholic schools understand the process and explore schools that might be right for their children. It features profiles of each school, frequently asked questions, information on scholarship programs, and an interactive Find a School tool. It\\u2019s the first time all of this information has been compiled in one publicly accessible online location.<\\/p>\\r\\n<h3>Why a guide to Catholic schools?<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>Over the last decade, New Orleans has invested heavily in its system of school choice and the infrastructure necessary to support it. Most notably, it adopted a universal enrollment system,&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.enrollnola.org\\/\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\" rel=\\\"noreferrer\\\">OneApp<\\/a>, to make the process of applying to public schools easier and fairer for families. Parents can use the system to view available schools and apply to those they prefer all at once. They also have access to the&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/neworleansparentsguide.org\\/\\\">New Orleans Parents Guide to Public Schools<\\/a>, Family Resource Centers, and other sources of information to help them make their choices.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>That\\u2019s not the case for the Catholic school system, however. Families interested in sending their children to Catholic schools have to research and apply to each school separately, and the process, requirements and timelines for applying differ from school to school. Then there\\u2019s the added complexity of applying for the three different kinds of scholarships available to lower-income students, which involves unraveling a whole new tangle of timelines and eligibility criteria.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>All of this translates to a lot of work and stress for parents. Overwhelmed by the prospect of researching schools, submitting applications, and figuring out the finances, many give up and don\\u2019t bother considering Catholic schools at all. It effectively puts off-limits a wide swath of local schools, particularly for parents who may not have the time or resources to deal with all the logistical demands. &nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n<h3>We wanted to make it easier.<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>Catholic schools have a long history in New Orleans, and many families love the values- and faith-based education they provide.&nbsp; We know Catholic schools aren\\u2019t right for everyone, but we believe that families should be aware of ALL of their school options and empowered to pursue any school that might be a good fit for their children. Confusing processes and unclear information should never stand in their way.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>The guide was created with great cooperation from the Office of Catholic Schools at the Archdiocese of New Orleans.&nbsp; We see it as a work in progress. Our team spent time surveying and meeting with school leaders to hear what they wanted to share with prospective families about their schools, and we are grateful to all the educators who contributed to it. Not all schools provided full information, but we plan to update the school profiles with additional data as we receive it. In the future, we also hope to add new information that gives families greater insight into each school and its success with students, in particular.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>For now, we hope the guide serves as a useful starting point for families who are interested in Catholic schools and want to narrow down their options. Check it out at&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/catholicschoolguide.ednavigator.com\\/\\\">www.catholicschoolsguide.ednavigator.com<\\/a>&nbsp;and please share it with anyone who might benefit.<\\/p>\",\"82\":\"The EdNavigator Guide to Catholic Schools in New Orleans features profiles of 80+ schools, frequently asked questions, information on scholarship programs, and an interactive Find a School tool.\",\"86\":[\"2978\"],\"88\":[\"2990\"],\"85\":\"\"}}', '2017-02-08 21:28:24', '2017-02-08 21:28:24', 'bd8dd3b1-6c5f-4e7e-b590-813e3f2f4846'),
 ('348', '2979', '11', '1', 'en_us', '3', '', '{\"typeId\":\"11\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"10 Common Questions about OneApp, Answered\",\"slug\":\"10-common-questions-about-oneapp-answered\",\"postDate\":1486416480,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"50\":[\"2977\"],\"49\":\"<p>Believe it or not, it\'s school choice season again for New Orleans families. To help you through the process, we\'ve compiled a list of some of the most common questions we hear about it.<\\/p>\\r\\n<h3>1. What is OneApp, anyway?<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>OneApp is New Orleans\\u2019 centralized school enrollment system. Unlike most cities around the country, where your home address determines where your children go to school, New Orleans allows families to choose their schools. &nbsp;If you want your child to attend a public school in Orleans Parish, it\\u2019s the system you need to use to select your school preferences and submit your application. OneApp is operated by EnrollNOLA, which is part of the Recovery School District.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><em>See also:<\\/em><\\/p>\\r\\n<ul><li><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/enrollnola.org\\/\\\">EnrollNOLA\\u2019s website<\\/a><\\/li><li><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.nola.com\\/education\\/index.ssf\\/2016\\/11\\/oneapp_basics_parents.html\\\">OneApp Basics for Parents via NOLA.com<\\/a><\\/li><li><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/enrollnola.org\\/about\\/about-oneapp\\/\\\">OneApp 101 via EnrollNOLA<\\/a><\\/li><li><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/vimeo.com\\/152376137\\\">Spanish Version of OneApp\'s Informational Video<\\/a><\\/li><\\/ul>\\r\\n<h3>&nbsp;<\\/h3>\\r\\n<h3>2. So can I apply to&nbsp;<em>any<\\/em>&nbsp;school in New Orleans through OneApp?<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>No. Almost every public school in New Orleans utilizes OneApp, but there are some exceptions. Audubon Charter, Ben Franklin High, Edward Hynes, Lake Forest Charter, Lusher Charter, New Orleans Center for Creative Arts (NOCCA) and Robert Moton Charter are not in OneApp. If you\\u2019re interested in these schools, you\\u2019ll need to&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.ednavigator.com\\/blog\\/2015\\/11\\/30\\/how-to-apply-to-a-non-oneapp-school-in-new-orleans\\\">apply to them separately<\\/a>. Since they are selective enrollment schools that draw lots of applications every year, we\\u2019d recommend that you apply to a few public schools via OneApp as well. &nbsp;Private schools, including most of New Orleans\\u2019 many Catholic schools, are not in OneApp either (the exception here: Catholic schools that accept&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/catholicschoolguide.ednavigator.com\\/paying-for-catholic-school\\/the-louisiana-scholarship-program\\\">Louisiana Scholarship Program<\\/a>&nbsp;vouchers).<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><em>See also:<\\/em><\\/p>\\r\\n<ul><li><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.ednavigator.com\\/blog\\/2015\\/11\\/30\\/how-to-apply-to-a-non-oneapp-school-in-new-orleans\\\">How to Apply for a Non-OneApp School<\\/a><\\/li><li><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/catholicschoolguide.ednavigator.com\\/\\\">EdNavigator\\u2019s Guide to Catholic Schools in New Orleans<\\/a><\\/li><\\/ul>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n<h3>3. When do I need to worry about all this?<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>Sooner than you think! The OneApp process starts early \\u2013 about nine months before the start of the school year. Here are the big dates for 2016-17:<\\/p>\\r\\n<ul><li>Application Opens:&nbsp;<strong>November 1, 2016<\\/strong><\\/li><li>Early Application Deadline:&nbsp;<strong>December 16, 2016<\\/strong><\\/li><li>Schools Expo 2017:&nbsp;<strong>February 4, 2017<\\/strong><\\/li><li>Main Round Application Deadline:&nbsp;<strong>February 24, 2017<\\/strong><\\/li><li>Main Round Results Available:&nbsp;<strong>Week of April 10, 2017<\\/strong><\\/li><li>Seat Acceptance Deadline:&nbsp;<strong>May 12, 2017<\\/strong><\\/li><\\/ul>\\r\\n<p>Another application round takes place later in the year, for families who were not able to participate in the main round or were not assigned a school (more on that below). You have the best chances of getting into one of your preferred schools if you apply by the main round application deadline, though, so&nbsp;<em>don\\u2019t miss it<\\/em>.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n<h3>4. How many schools can I apply for in OneApp?<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>OneApp allows families to apply to up to eight participating schools. Keep in mind that your child will only be accepted to ONE school from your list, and there are no re-dos. Don\\u2019t include any school you wouldn\\u2019t be comfortable having your child attend. Be realistic though; if you\\u2019re applying for one of New Orleans\\u2019 most popular schools, consider including a backup school that would still be a good fit for your child, but sees less demand.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n<h3>5. How do I figure out which schools might be the right fit?<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>The downside of having so many choices is that sorting through them isn\\u2019t always easy.&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/enrollnola.org\\/k12\\/\\\">EnrollNOLA\\u2019s school finder tool<\\/a>&nbsp;is a good place to start. It allows you to narrow down your options based on things like locations and state letter grades. Once you have a short list of possibilities, we\\u2019d recommend visiting the schools (many offer open houses) and talking to other families to get a better feel for them.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>See also:<\\/p>\\r\\n<ul><li><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.nola.com\\/education\\/index.ssf\\/2016\\/11\\/2016_performance_score_databas.html\\\">2016 School Grades\\/Performance Scores<\\/a><\\/li><li><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.ednavigator.com\\/blog\\/2016\\/5\\/2\\/whats-the-measure-of-a-good-school\\\">EdNavigator\\u2019s 2016 Adjusted School Grades<\\/a><\\/li><li><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/neworleansparentsguide.org\\/\\\">New Orleans Parents\\u2019 Guide to Public Schools<\\/a><\\/li><\\/ul>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n<h3>6. My child\\u2019s already in a school that we like. Do I still need to participate in OneApp?<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>No. If your child is happy at their current school, you should NOT submit a OneApp. If you do submit a OneApp and they are assigned to a school on that application, your child WILL lose the guarantee on the spot at their current school assignment.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n<h3>7. Am I guaranteed to get one of the schools I list?<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>Unfortunately, no. It\\u2019s possible that you may not get any of your choices (which could happen if you only indicate one or two very in-demand schools, for instance), in which case you would repeat the process again in the next round. For this reason, it\\u2019s a good idea to include a mix of schools \\u2013 but&nbsp;<em>only<\\/em>&nbsp;schools that you would be comfortable with your child attending.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p><em>See also:<\\/em><\\/p>\\r\\n<ul><li><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/vimeo.com\\/152375695\\\">How OneApp Works (EnrollNOLA Video)<\\/a><\\/li><\\/ul>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n<h3>8. How do I submit an application?<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>You can do it&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/enrollnola.org\\/how-to-enroll-in-nops\\/apply-transfer-next-school-year\\/\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\" rel=\\\"noreferrer\\\">online<\\/a>. If you prefer, you can also visit one of EnrollNOLA\\u2019s three&nbsp;<a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/enrollnola.org\\/resources\\/family-resource-centers\\/\\\">Family Resource Centers<\\/a>&nbsp;to do it in person. In addition to providing free access to computers for families who would like to fill out the application online, the Resource Centers are staffed with school choice advisors who can help answer basic questions. You can also get help with general questions by contacting EnrollNOLA at 877-343-4773.<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n<h3>9. What if I don\\u2019t speak English?<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>There are Spanish and Vietnamese versions of OneApp online for families. The Family Resource Centers also have access to translators.&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n<p>&nbsp;<\\/p>\\r\\n<h3>10. I got started and now I\\u2019m totally overwhelmed. What do I do?<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>Before you start checking out real estate listings in other parishes, take a deep breath. OneApp is designed to be easy to use, but it\\u2019s also easy to get confused. Choosing the right school for your child is a huge responsibility! Feel free to reach out to us via email at&nbsp;<a href=\\\"mailto:info@ednavigator.com\\\">info@ednavigator.com<\\/a>&nbsp;if you\\u2019d like to talk to one of our Navigators about your options.<\\/p>\",\"82\":\"We\'ll start with the basics: \\\"What is OneApp, anyway?\\\"\",\"86\":[\"2978\"],\"88\":[\"2991\"],\"85\":\"\"}}', '2017-02-08 21:28:33', '2017-02-08 21:28:33', 'd45e6954-e824-4e74-bbd2-5ace97817e17'),
